WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.040
I'm going to talk about semacell as part of a frontline approach to diffuse large B-cell

00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:08.200
lymphoma patients who are likely to relapse.

00:00:08.440 --> 00:00:09.740
These are my disclosures.

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:16.100
So for patients with diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, most patients achieve a response

00:00:16.100 --> 00:00:19.400
after frontline immunochemotherapy approaches.

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:27.760
And of those patients, approximately two-thirds maintained long-term remissions or cures,

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:29.800
and about a third of patients relapse.

00:00:30.620 --> 00:00:35.940
Currently, our standard of care in terms of monitoring those patients is, for the most

00:00:35.940 --> 00:00:37.360
part, a watch and wait approach.

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:41.400
Sometimes we do surveillance imaging in follow-up.

00:00:41.460 --> 00:00:42.560
Some of us don't do that.

00:00:43.220 --> 00:00:48.140
And the question is, if we could identify these patients who are going to relapse earlier,

00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:49.840
would they have a better outcome?

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:56.460
I think it's really interesting that about 15% of patients get CAR-T-cells in second-line

00:00:56.460 --> 00:00:56.740
treatment.

00:00:56.740 --> 00:00:58.760
So the number is actually low.

00:00:59.080 --> 00:00:59.940
And one of the reasons.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.100
For that, it's a lot of patients, when they progress, they have advanced disease, they

00:01:04.100 --> 00:01:09.060
have extranodal disease that might exclude them from some of these therapies.

00:01:09.240 --> 00:01:15.880
So the question of this study is, we know that MRD at the end of therapy is predictive

00:01:15.880 --> 00:01:16.840
of outcome.

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:23.500
And if you are MRD positive, but you have a CR or PR, if you get soma cell, is that

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:26.940
associated with an improved EFS over observation?

00:01:29.620 --> 00:01:38.720
So we know that MRD detection by ctDNA is a promising method for early relapse prediction

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:39.900
in large B-cell lymphoma.

00:01:40.020 --> 00:01:44.700
And a lot of this work was done by Wyndham and Ash.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:52.260
We know that in the interim setting, at the end of therapy, that if you're MRD positive

00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:58.420
and you have large B-cell lymphoma, that this is associated with a worse event-free

00:01:58.420 --> 00:01:58.980
survival.

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:08.060
And if we compare MRD to PET, the diagnostic threshold for ctDNA is lower than for PET,

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:08.900
as shown here.

00:02:08.900 --> 00:02:13.760
And this is potentially very important in patients who relapse, if you can detect a

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:16.400
relapse earlier rather than later.

00:02:18.100 --> 00:02:29.200
And there are a number of different ways of looking at ctDNA, and one of those is a phase-seq

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:29.740
assay.

00:02:30.020 --> 00:02:32.180
And this is the test that is used in the study.

00:02:32.560 --> 00:02:34.660
It's the foresight clarity test.

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:42.580
And there was a recent prospective multicenter validation study that looked at patients treated

00:02:42.580 --> 00:02:49.220
in the frontline setting with diffuse large B-cell lymphoma and compared the predictive

00:02:49.220 --> 00:02:52.480
value of end-of-therapy PET to end-of-therapy ctDNA.

00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:59.180
And you can see here, if you look at progression-free survival, the PET positive patients are, you

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:03.120
can see here, on the lower curve and negative around the upper curve, and likewise with

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:03.640
ctDNA.

00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:10.280
But you can see that ctDNA is more sensitive in predicting progression than PET.

00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:22.960
So are we in the process of changing the paradigm of how we approach potential relapse patients

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:24.840
with large B-cell lymphoma?

00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:28.920
And should we be using ctDNA?

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:36.360
To guide early intervention, MRD predicts risk of relapse as shown here.

00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:48.220
And if you look at the disease burden of patients who relapse clinically by clinical presentation

00:03:48.220 --> 00:03:56.360
or by imaging versus those who are positive by end-of-therapy MRD and are in CRPR, their

00:03:56.360 --> 00:03:58.900
disease burden is much, much lower.

00:03:58.900 --> 00:04:05.140
At the end of therapy, and in large-cell therapeutics, we know certainly in the frontline setting

00:04:05.140 --> 00:04:08.800
that if you have lower burden disease, you have a better outcome.

00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:14.660
So the drug that is being investigated is Semacel.

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:18.400
It's an anti-CD19 allogeneic CAR-T cell.

00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:26.440
And one of the advantages, of course, of this is that it can be given to patients very quickly.

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:35.940
It's derived from healthy donors, but patients can potentially have immediate access to cell therapy

00:04:35.940 --> 00:04:41.620
that is allogeneic versus autologous, which takes some time to produce.

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:50.540
So the product has been tested in the relapsed refractory setting in patients,

00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:55.320
principally with diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, but also with other B-cell lymphomas.

00:04:56.080 --> 00:04:58.420
And this was published last year.

00:04:58.880 --> 00:05:07.160
And in terms of efficacy, Semacel was associated with an overall response rate of 58%

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:10.440
with 42% of patients achieving a CR.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:16.640
And if you look at the duration of responses and the duration of CRs, they're shown here.

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:23.220
And they are, I think it's fair to say, similar to autologous CAR-T cell results.

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:28.520
Also, in terms of safety, in the relapsed refractory setting,

00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:30.180
the product was safe.

00:05:30.240 --> 00:05:33.540
If you look at CRS and ICANS and graft-versus-host disease,

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:39.540
these were very low throughout the study and at the selected Phase II dose.

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:45.420
So the current Alpha-3 Phase II design is shown here.

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:51.160
So patients have a new diagnosis of large B-cell lymphoma, including diffuse large B-cell lymphoma,

00:05:51.240 --> 00:05:54.320
high-grade B-cell lymphoma, and primary mediastinal B-cell lymphoma.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:58.840
And at the end of immunochemotherapy, they are safe.

00:05:58.840 --> 00:06:05.620
And if they are in remission by endotherapy PET with a CR or a PR,

00:06:06.340 --> 00:06:12.500
and if they are MRD positive, then they're randomized to either get lymphodepletion chemotherapy

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:14.660
and Semacel or observation.

00:06:15.360 --> 00:06:18.280
Study is divided into two parts, Part A and Part B.

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:22.940
Part A is currently being analyzed at the moment.

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:28.380
So there's an interim of safety and biomarker-based futility analysis ongoing.

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:30.580
And Part B of the study has started.

00:06:31.880 --> 00:06:37.320
And I've talked about the eligibility in terms of large B-cell lymphoma subtypes.

00:06:37.800 --> 00:06:40.480
The study is ongoing throughout various centers.

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:50.000
So in conclusion, the Alpha-3 study is looking at large B-cell lymphoma patients that are in CR or PR.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:58.600
And the question is if you are and you are MRD positive, is intervening with this agent,

00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:02.740
is it associated with a better survival compared to observation?

00:07:02.740 --> 00:07:04.780
And we'll have a discussion and questions later.

00:07:04.780 --> 00:07:05.380
Thank you.
